---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Erikson: Identity Crisis and the Eight Stages of Psychosocial Development | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Erikson</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Identity Crisis and the Eight Stages of Psychosocial Development
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The developmental framework of identity formation through normative psychosocial crises across the entire lifespan, with identity crisis as the central task of adolescence.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Erikson in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering. Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective. The purpose here is not to describe Erikson in his full being, but to distill the essential stance relevant to identity and learn from him within this framework. That is not a claim to devalue his work or to say it would be invalid when read on its own terms.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Psychosocial Development and the Epigenetic Principle</div>
					<p>
						Erik Erikson extended Freudian psychoanalysis into a lifespan model of psychosocial development. He proposed eight stages, each defined by a central crisis that must be resolved for healthy development. The principle is epigenetic: each stage builds on the previous ones and prepares the ground for the next.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						The stages are:
						Trust vs. Mistrust (infancy), Autonomy vs. Shame/Doubt (early childhood), Initiative vs. Guilt (preschool), Industry vs. Inferiority (school age), Identity vs. Role Confusion (adolescence), Intimacy vs. Isolation (young adulthood), Generativity vs. Stagnation (middle adulthood), and Ego Integrity vs. Despair (late adulthood).
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Identity Crisis as the Central Task</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core concept (Erikson):</strong> Adolescence is the stage of Identity vs. Role Confusion. The central task is to form a coherent, stable sense of identity: a sense of who one is, what one stands for, and where one is going. Failure leads to role confusion and a fragmented sense of self.
					</div>
					<p>
						Identity is not just an internal psychological structure but psychosocial: it is formed in relationship to society, culture, and significant others. A strong identity provides a sense of continuity, direction, and commitment.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						The later stages (Generativity and Ego Integrity) concern leaving a legacy and affirming one’s life as meaningful, tasks that require a sufficiently coherent identity to have been formed earlier.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Erikson:</strong> identity develops through structured crises and stages. It is not static but unfolds over time, with specific windows where conscious work can have outsized impact on the overall geometry.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> crises as high-curvature moments; the Stem as something that is tested and strengthened (or weakened) at each stage; and later-life tasks (Generativity, Ego Integrity) as the long-term fruits of earlier geometric work.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Identity crisis as high-curvature window:</strong> Erikson suggests that adolescence (and other transition points) can be periods of heightened plasticity. These are strong moments for deliberate Questions as Probes and conscious curvature of identity geometry, because the Stem may be especially open to reconfiguration.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Stage-specific Stem formation:</strong> Each stage presents a specific challenge to the coherence and strength of the Stem (trust, autonomy, initiative, industry, identity, intimacy, generativity, integrity). Successful resolution adds Mass and stability; failure creates vulnerabilities that later stages must compensate for.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Generativity and Ego Integrity as long-term fruits:</strong> The later stages concern leaving a meaningful legacy and affirming one’s life. These are the downstream consequences of earlier geometric work, and they are a practical test of whether the identity geometry supports open, generative, and integrated futures.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Psychosocial embeddedness:</strong> Identity is never purely individual. Erikson reminds us that the Stem is always formed in relation to culture, relationships, and historical context (echoing Heidegger’s thrownness and Sartre’s intersubjectivity).
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Erikson provides a structured, lifespan developmental model that bridges the philosophical and depth-psychological anchors with empirical psychology. He complements Jung’s lifelong individuation process by giving it concrete stages and crises. He complements Sartre and Heidegger by showing how identity formation is not only a matter of radical choice or ontological structures but also of normative developmental tasks that society and relationships impose and support.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary works: Erik H. Erikson, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Childhood and Society</em> (1950), <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Identity: Youth and Crisis</em> (1968), <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">The Life Cycle Completed</em> (1982).
						</li>
						<li>
							Biographical and stage overview: Encyclopaedia Britannica, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Erik-Erikson" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Erik Erikson</a> (updated 2026).
						</li>
						<li>
							Context reference: Encyclopaedia Britannica, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/psychological-development" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">psychological development</a> (lifespan context and related developmental framing).
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Erikson is the major developmental-psychological anchor. He provides a structured, lifespan model of how identity forms and transforms through normative crises. This anchor bridges the philosophical and depth-psychological foundations with a more empirical understanding of developmental windows and the relational/cultural embeddedness of identity.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
